    <h5 class="offcanvas-title" id="offcanvasBottomLabel">Understanding Options Greeks - Better Trading Guide</h5>
    <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="offcanvas" aria-label="Close"></button>
  </div>
  <div class="offcanvas-body small">
    <button onclick="shareOnTwitter('Checkout this blog about OPTION GREEKS IN STOCK MARKET by @HSJNFinWisdom', 'CARD2')" class="tweet">Click To Share <i class="fa-brands fa-twitter"></i></button>
    <br><br>
    <p class="para">
      Options Greeks are a set of mathematical measurements that help traders to understand the risks and rewards associated with options trading. These measurements are derived from the option's price, the underlying asset's price, and the time until the option expires. There are four main Options Greeks:
      <span style="color: #00a88c">
        Delta,
        Theta,
        Gamma,
        Vega
      </span>.
    </p>
    <div class="para">
      <b><u>DELTA ( Δ )</u></b>
      <br>
      <ul class="para" style="text-align: left; list-style-type: square;">
        <li>
          <b>Definition: </b>It measures the sensitivity of the option's price to changes in the underlying asset's price. It represents the expected change in the option price for a one-point change in the price of the underlying asset.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Range: </b>It values range from -1 to 1 for individual options. Call options have positive delta (typically between 0 and 1), while put options have negative delta (typically between 0 and -1). <i>It can be thought of as the probability that the option will expire in-the-money.</i>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="para">
      <b><u>THETA ( θ )</u></b>
      <br>
      <ul class="para" style="text-align: left; list-style-type: square;">
        <li>
          <b>Definition: </b>It measures the sensitivity of the option's price to the passage of time. It represents the change in the option price per unit of time, often expressed in days.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Sign: </b>It is always negative for both call and put options. This is because options generally lose value as time passes, assuming all other factors remain constant.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="para">
      <b><u>GAMMA ( Γ )</u></b>
      <br>
      <ul class="para" style="text-align: left; list-style-type: square;">
        <li>
          <b>Definition: </b> It measures the rate of change of an option's delta in response to a one-point change in the price of the underlying asset.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Importance: </b>It is crucial for understanding how delta itself changes as the underlying asset's price changes. It is particularly relevant for traders who want to hedge their delta exposure or adjust their positions dynamically.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="para">
      <b><u>VEGA ( ν )</u></b>
      <br>
      <ul class="para" style="text-align: left; list-style-type: square;">
        <li>
          <b>Definition: </b>It measures the sensitivity of the option's price to changes in implied volatility, which is the market's expectation of future price volatility.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Importance: </b>It is essential for traders who want to assess the impact of changes in market volatility on their options positions. Higher vega values indicate that the option's price is more sensitive to changes in implied volatility.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p class="para">
      In summary, these Greek letters provide insights into different aspects of options pricing and help traders make informed decisions based on their risk tolerance and market expectations. It's important to note that these sensitivities are interconnected, and changes in one Greek can influence the behavior of others.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

